<taxonomicName box="[305,519,1095,1117]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="171" pageNumber="172" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="erylicola" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[305,519,1095,1117]" italics="true" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">
<taxonomicName box="[305,424,1095,1117]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="171" pageNumber="172" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Spirastrella</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[429,519,1095,1117]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172" rank="species" species="erylicola" status="sp. nov.">erylicola</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[525,605,1095,1116]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[525,605,1095,1116]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, a, habitus of holotype RMNH Por. 10535 (scale bar = 1 cm), b–c, SEM images of the spicules, b, tylostyle, b1, details of b, c, spiraster, c1, spiraster with secondary spines, c2, younger forms of the spirasters.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="171.[151,1437,1187,1788]" box="[199,716,1187,1212]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,1187,1212]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">Spicules.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[319,417,1187,1212]" captionStart="FIGURE 107" captionStartId="171.[151,250,1095,1117]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1074]" captionTargetId="figure@171.[151,1436,193,1074]" captionTargetPageId="171" captionText="FIGURE 107. Spirastrella erylicola sp. nov., a, habitus of holotype RMNH Por. 10535 (scale bar = 1 cm), b – c, SEM images of the spicules, b, tylostyle, b 1, details of b, c, spiraster, c 1, spiraster with secondary spines, c 2, younger forms of the spirasters." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273057/files/figure.png" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">Figs 107</figureCitation>
b–c) Tylostyles, spirasters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="171.[151,1437,1187,1788]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">
Tylostyles (
<figureCitation box="[328,432,1223,1248]" captionStart="FIGURE 107" captionStartId="171.[151,250,1095,1117]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1074]" captionTargetId="figure@171.[151,1436,193,1074]" captionTargetPageId="171" captionText="FIGURE 107. Spirastrella erylicola sp. nov., a, habitus of holotype RMNH Por. 10535 (scale bar = 1 cm), b – c, SEM images of the spicules, b, tylostyle, b 1, details of b, c, spiraster, c 1, spiraster with secondary spines, c 2, younger forms of the spirasters." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273057/files/figure.png" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">Figs 107</figureCitation>
b,b1), curved, with prominent heads and sharply pointed apices, 570– 
<emphasis box="[1205,1247,1223,1247]" italics="true" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">744</emphasis>
–882 
<date box="[1310,1344,1223,1248]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">x 6</date>
– 
<emphasis box="[1359,1394,1223,1247]" italics="true" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">9.3</emphasis>
–13 µm (heads 9– 
<emphasis box="[304,353,1260,1284]" italics="true" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">12.8</emphasis>
–18 µm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="171.[151,1437,1187,1788]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">
Spirasters (
<figureCitation box="[325,429,1295,1320]" captionStart="FIGURE 107" captionStartId="171.[151,250,1095,1117]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1074]" captionTargetId="figure@171.[151,1436,193,1074]" captionTargetPageId="171" captionText="FIGURE 107. Spirastrella erylicola sp. nov., a, habitus of holotype RMNH Por. 10535 (scale bar = 1 cm), b – c, SEM images of the spicules, b, tylostyle, b 1, details of b, c, spiraster, c 1, spiraster with secondary spines, c 2, younger forms of the spirasters." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273057/files/figure.png" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">Figs 107</figureCitation>
c,c1,c2), in the form of singly curved asters, spines conical, compound; smaller forms are few, supposedly juvenile stages, including thinly spined forms, overall diameters 13– 
<emphasis box="[1105,1154,1331,1356]" italics="true" pageId="171" pageNumber="172">18.6</emphasis>
–23 µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1392,1367,1392]" pageId="171" pageNumber="172" type="distribution">
